        <para> Before introducing Tamboti's Basic Input forms, we need to talk a little about the
            structure of bibliographical entries in general. </para>
        <para>There are many different kinds of bibliographical items, but for our purposes the most
            important among them are 
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>Book: A work of writing on a single subject, published as one or
                    more book volumes. A book may occur in a
                    book series.</listitem>
                <listitem>Article: A work of writing on a single subject, published in a
                    periodical.</listitem>
                <listitem>Contributions to edited volumes: Publications which resemble articles, but which occur (along with other
                    similar publications) in books which are thematically unified and have an
                    editor. These contributions are often
                    referred to as "book chapters" or "chapters of edited volumes".</listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </para>
        <para>The above list shows three categories you work with in Tamboti:
            <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>Book series</listitem>
                <listitem>Periodicals</listitem>
                <listitem>Edited volumes</listitem>
            </itemizedlist>
        </para>
        <para> Bibliographical entries divide into three blocks of information, that is,
            information concerning </para>
        <ul>
            <li>the publication itself
                <itemizedlist>
                    <listitem>a book</listitem>
                    <listitem>an article</listitem>
                    <listitem>a contribution to an edited volume</listitem>
                </itemizedlist>
            </li>
            <li>the container that the publication occurs in
                <itemizedlist>
                    <listitem>a book series</listitem>
                    <listitem>a periodical</listitem>
                    <listitem>an edited volume</listitem>
                </itemizedlist>
            </li>
            <li>the location of the publication inside its container.</li>
        </ul>
        <para>Books that belong in a book series, articles that belong in a periodical,
            and contributions that belong in an edited volume all follow the above pattern. Books which are not part of a series only cover
            the first block of information. The last two blocks
            are simply left empty. The same applies to descriptions of series and periodicals as
            such.</para>
